    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "could it be a nitrogen issue specifically? i've heard about that. how would i even know if the soil is actually missing nitrogen vs just being the wrong pH?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Nitrogen deficiency is a very common culprit, and it certainly presents with those lower, yellowing leaves, which is a classic sign. The way to tell if it's nitrogen versus pH is to get a soil test, which is the most definitive way to know what your soil is lacking. If you don't want to test, you can try applying a nitrogen-rich fertilizer and see if the new growth perks up, but be careful not to overdo it.",
      "source": "target",
