    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah a soil test makes sense. in the meantime, i'm worried about the nutrients just being... gone. like is it possible something else is just sucking them out of the soil faster than the plants can get them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that's a very valid concern, and it's often related to soil health and biology. Things like overly aggressive root competition or even certain types of soil-borne pests can act like little nutrient vacuums, sucking up what the tomatoes need. It's a good idea to keep an eye out for any signs of root damage or excessive insect activity near the base of the plants. Sometimes, a soil amendment like compost can help replenish and stabilize those nutrients faster than the plants can pull them out.",
      "source": "target",
